python hunt, we do participate year-round in fieldwork researching Florida\u2019s invasive species issue with pythons.\n \nNaples Zoo proudly supports two conservation partners working on this challenging problem: the Conservancy of Southwest Florida (which has removed over 1,300 pythons weighing more than 36,000 pounds) and the python program at Big Cypress National Preserve (Big Cypress), which is a partnership between the National Park Service (NPS) and U. S. Geological Survey (USGS). Over the past several years, our veterinary staff have assisted the Big Cypress program by surgically implanting tracking devices into large pythons, then joining field teams to track and X-ray these snakes to learn what they are eating and how they impact our ecosystem.\n \nAfter a quick check-up and X-rays, this 17-foot, 165 pound, tagged python was released so USGS and NPS scientists can continue monitoring its movements. Tracking these snakes over time reveals where they hide, breed, and hunt, this information helps wildlife managers locate and remove even more invasive pythons from Florida\u2019s
